flowRoot.flowPara: A person can spread the flu to you if a droplet made when they cough, sneeze or talk lands in your mouth, nose or if you inhale it. You can get the flu from someone up to 6 feet away.
You can also get the flu if you touch a surface or object that someone with the flu has touched; then touch your mouth or nose.
It takes 1 to 4 days for symptoms to show once the virus enters your body. This means you can spread the flu 1 day before symptoms develop and up to 5-7 days after becoming sick.
You can also become infected with the flu virus but have no symptoms.
- Fever or chills
(not everyone with flu will have a fever)
- Cough
- Sore throat
- Runny or stuffy nose
- Muscle or body aches
- Headaches
- Fatigue (tiredness)
- Vomiting and diarrhea
(more common in children)
Seasonal influenza, commonly called "the flu," is caused by the influenza viruses, which infects the respiratory tract (i.e., the nose, throat, lungs).
Unlike the common cold, the flu can cause severe illness and life-threatening complications.
The flu can cause mild to severe illness, and at times it can lead to death. It is estimated that over 200,000 people in the U.S. are hospitalized due to flu-related complications.

The FluMeter uses transmission risk contour maps from empirical research and up-to-date weather information from worldweatheronline.com to estimate the potential of contracting influenza relative to the temperature and humidity of a location.

flowRoot.flowPara: Information for Nationwide Info is compiled directly from the Center for Disease Control’s Flu Report.
Explanations of activity levels:
No Activity: No laboratory-confirmed influenza cases (LCIC) and no reported increase in the number of cases of Influenza-like Illness (ILI).
Sporadic: Small numbers of LCIC or a single influenza outbreak reported, but no increase in ILI.
Local: A region of the state reported outbreaks of LCIC or increases in ILI.
Regional: In at least 2 regions of the state, but less than half, reported LCIC outbreaks or increases in ILI.
Widespread: At least half of the state regions reported LCIC outbreaks or increases in ILI .
The information contained in these pages was collected from the Center for Disease Control website.
Flu is a serious contagious disease that can lead to hospitalization and even death.
1) Get the flu vaccine – every year
2) Cover your nose and mouth with your elbow or a tissue when you cough or sneeze.
3) Wash your hands with soap and water or use an alcohol-based hand rub.
4) Avoid touching your eyes, nose and mouth.
5) Avoid close contact with sick people.
1) Seek medical help from your doctor for an accurate diagnosis
2) Ask your doctor for antiviral drugs which can make the illness milder and shorten the time you are sick. They may also prevent serious flu complications
3) Stay home for at least 24 hours after your fever is gone (except to get medical care)
4) Limit contact with others to so they too don’t become ill.
